From: Vansh Singh Ruhela <hadesllm@proton.me>
Subject: [PATCH 2/2] xfrm: esp4/esp6: disable in-place AEAD on splice-pinned frags

esp_output_tail() defaults to esp->inplace = true, in which case the
AEAD scatterlist uses dsg == sg --- the same scatterlist for source
and destination.  When the skb has frags whose underlying pages came
from MSG_SPLICE_PAGES, the in-place AEAD writes ciphertext back into
pages still mapped into userspace, which is the xfrm half of the
Dirty Frag chain disclosed on oss-security 2026-05-07.

Force the non-inplace path (which allocates a fresh destination page
from x->xfrag) whenever the skb is shared, has a frag_list, or has
any frag at all.  The check is intentionally conservative ---
nr_frags > 0 captures all frag-bearing skbs, including ones whose
frags are kernel-allocated and therefore safe.  Trading fast-path
performance for safety is the right default until a finer
``frag-is-user-pinned" predicate exists.

esp6.c has the same structure and gets the same patch.  This patch
is the esp4.c half; the esp6.c patch will be sent immediately after
in this series (or as part of this one if list policy allows
combined IPv4/IPv6 patches; please advise).

Reported-by: oss-security 2026-05-07/8 (Dirty Frag)
Fixes: <commit hash for the MSG_SPLICE_PAGES adoption in esp_output_tail — to be filled in after `git log -p` on the upstream tree>
Cc: security@kernel.org
Cc: stable@vger.kernel.org
Cc: Herbert Xu <herbert@gondor.apana.org.au>
Cc: netdev@vger.kernel.org
Signed-off-by: Vansh Singh Ruhela <hadesllm@proton.me>
Co-developed-by: Yoda <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 net/ipv4/esp4.c | 11 +++++++++++
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+)

diff --git a/net/ipv4/esp4.c b/net/ipv4/esp4.c
index 1234567..abcdefg 100644
--- a/net/ipv4/esp4.c
+++ b/net/ipv4/esp4.c
@@ -495,6 +495,17 @@ int esp_output_tail(struct xfrm_state *x, struct sk_buff *skb, struct esp_info *
 	struct esp_output_extra *extra;
 	int err = -ENOMEM;

+	/* Dirty Frag (oss-security 2026-05-07): the in-place AEAD path
+	 * uses dsg == sg, so crypto writes back to the same skb pages we
+	 * read from.  This is unsafe when any frag came from
+	 * MSG_SPLICE_PAGES without a copy-on-write boundary.  Force the
+	 * non-inplace path (which allocates fresh destination pages from
+	 * x->xfrag) whenever the skb is shared or has any frag entries.
+	 */
+	if (esp->inplace &&
+	    (skb_shared(skb) || skb_has_frag_list(skb) ||
+	     skb_shinfo(skb)->nr_frags > 0))
+		esp->inplace = false;
+
 	assoclen = sizeof(struct ip_esp_hdr);
 	extralen = 0;

